Phylodynamic analysis of a COVID19 outbreak in Washington state

Josh Herbeck, modified from an original by Erik Volz

3/11/2020

This analysis was originally written by Erik Volz (I cloned his https://github.com/emvolz/weifang-sarscov2 repository). I haved edited it so the anlaysis is of the X available WA SARS-CoV-2 sequences (as of date Y), not Weifang SARS-CoV-2 sequences.

Preliminary phylogenetic analysis

Load the R packages

library( ape ) 
library( lubridate ) 
library( treedater )

Set the data directory and load the data

SARS-CoV-19 genomes are retrieved from: https://gisaid.org/CoV2020

“Via the Nextstrain genome alignment pipeline, remove the first 130 sites, the last 50 sites, and site 18529 from the alignment.”

data_dir <- "~/Dropbox/SARS-CoV-2/data"

Run RAxML to make an ML tree

#alignment.raxml.tree <- raxml(d, m = "GTRGAMMA", f = "d", N = 1)

We use the treedater R package. This takes the following inputs: dater(tree, sts, s) where * tree is an ape::phylo phylogeny object, * sts is a vector of sample times for each tip in tree formatted as fractions of the calendar year (e.g. 2010.1235) * s is the length of the genetic sequences used to estimate tree

Create the sts vector for treedater

sts <- sapply( strsplit( tr$tip.label, '\\|' ), function(x) (x[length(x)-1] ) )
sts <- as.numeric(sts)
#sts <- decimal_date(sts)
names(sts) <- tr$tip.label

#"USA/WA-UW52/2020|EPI_ISL_415617|2020-03-09|2020.186|_exog"

Run treedater

td <- dater( tr, sts, s = 29726 , searchRoot = 10, temporalConstraints=TRUE,
             meanRateLimits = c(.0007, .002) )

Treedater estimated tMRCA (time to most recent common ancestor) is 365*td$timeToMRCA days, and the date of common ancestor as date_decimal(td[[4]]).

BEAST phylodynamic analysis

Install BEAST2 from here: https://www.beast2.org/

BEAST input files

https://github.com/mrc-ide/PhyDyn/wiki/Structured-Tree-Likelihood#population-structure “Population structure is introduced by mapping tip nodes to deme names. This can be done by annotating the corresponding tree taxa ids with deme information or by introducing an extra type trait. With the former, taxa ids must be suffixed with an underscore followed by the deme information. For example, a tree tip annotated with taxon

“EBOV|G4973.1|KR105286|SLE|x|2014-08-12_I”

will be associated to deme I."

In BEAUti: load the alignment assign tip dates choose the HKY+G substitution model and the strict clock model.

Useful template for implementing the SEI(J)R runs: https://github.com/mrc-ide/PhyDyn/wiki/SEIR-Template

https://beast.community/online_inference
